I slightly improved the parsing code for the bam header reader and updated the test + test data to reflect this type of header.

See https://github.com/conda-forge/pykdtree-feedstock/pull/16

Basically to fulfill the GPL license, the source distribution should include a copy of the license file. This PR adds the license file to the sdist manifest. Also I added a `python_requires` which will help in the future if/when pykdtree drops python 2.7 support. It will make it so people downloading pykdtree from PyPI on python 2.7 don't get the version of the package that has dropped python 2.7 support.

@mraspaud I think I mentioned the need for this PR last week.

When subsequent payload to be pushed by mocket was shorter than previous one, additional data were dumped. This was because BytesIO object had longer length; calling truncate() on the BytesIO object solves this problem

code to reproduce the problem, before this patch:

```
@mocketize
def test_something():
    Mocket.register(
        MocketEntry(
            ('example.com', 80),
            [
                b'this is some long payload'
                b'short',
            ]
        ),
    )
```
then, when one would use socket object, and call `recv` on it, one would get part of the first payload with the second call

@mparent61 

* filters entries by published
* takes an array of entry ids rather than a timestamp

Created basic tree transformations (rotation, translation) which copy the tree every time they are applied. Rotation and translation are already tested separately. I will have to implement a thorough test for affineTransform when I move it inside neurom.

@lidakanari and everyone please let me know if other functionality is required as well.

@juanchopanza I am unsure where these functions should be moved. I would say morphtree but morphtree is in analysis and this is a little bit more invasive than analysis.

__NOTE__: This PR updates the `__version__` in cloudaux/__about__.py

* The previous PR mistakenly used Python's __HTTPException__ instead of __openstack.exceptions.HttpException__.  This PR properly imports and uses the latter.

@mikegrima

The dict that is passed in:
```
the_dict = {'params': {'test_key_here': 'value'}}
```

Output before:
```
  {
    "params": {
      "test_key_here": "value",
    }
  }
```

Output after:
```
  {
    "params": {
      "testKeyHere": "value",
    }
  }
```

Added a 'silent' option to _settings in fitter.  If True then the plot settings are not printed when sm.fit(), or sm.set_data() is called.

This can be improved.  This should probably set autoplot = False in the settings dict, for example.  Also, it is looking at the zeroth element of a list...  It works in limited use.

@jaxankey

It is to fix the attach failure case with following steps:
1. Device join network as a router, the network information will be stored locally;
2. Reset device, and it will restore the network information;
3. Execute `routerrole disable` command to disable router capacity;
4. Execute `thread start` command to start attach;
5. Device will try to start Router Synchronization process in `BecomeRouter()`, but it will fail due to `VerifyOrExit(IsRouterRoleEnabled(), error = kThreadError_NotCapable);`.

I think this fixes the test that keeps randomly failing, e.g. for 
40835b2 

@Dominik-Vogel @sohailc
